  <content>
    <title>Build vs Buy Decision Framework</title>

    <summary>Evaluate whether to build a capability in-house, buy a vendor solution, or adopt a hybrid approach. The framework covers strategic fit (core vs context), 3-year TCO comparison, vendor evaluation, risk assessment, and exit strategy documentation. Organizations with proprietary core technology see ~2x stronger revenue growth (Deloitte 2025).</summary>

    <why>
      <p>67% of failed software implementations stem from incorrect build vs buy decisions (Forrester 2024). Building non-differentiating capabilities wastes engineering time that could go to competitive advantage. Buying core capabilities creates vendor lock-in and limits adaptability. The decision requires systematic analysis of strategic fit, total cost of ownership, team capabilities, and vendor stability — not just initial license cost.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Evaluating any capability that requires significant investment: authentication, billing, search, notifications, analytics, storage.</item>
        <item>When the team is considering a SaaS solution with multi-year subscription costs.</item>
        <item>When open-source alternatives exist alongside commercial options.</item>
        <item>Before starting a major new subsystem build — always evaluate buy first.</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Core competitive differentiators — the capability that makes your product unique should almost always be built, not bought.</item>
        <item>When the buy option has no viable exit path — vendor lock-in without a documented exit strategy is a separate risk requiring explicit acceptance.</item>
        <item>Commodity infrastructure already standardized in your stack (e.g., "should we use Redis or build a cache?") — existing standards override the analysis.</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="strategic-assessment">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Before comparing costs, classify the capability as: Core (direct competitive advantage — prefer build), Context (necessary but not differentiating — prefer buy if mature market exists), or Commodity (standard capability with many providers — always buy). Only Core capabilities justify custom development at startup scale.</statement>
        <rationale>Organizations with proprietary core technology see ~2x stronger revenue growth (Deloitte 2025). Building context and commodity capabilities diverts engineering from the core. The classification must be documented and agreed by product and technical stakeholders before TCO analysis begins.</rationale>
      </rule>

      <example type="good" title="Build vs buy — authentication for B2B SaaS">
        <code lang="text"><![CDATA[Context: B2B SaaS, enterprise auth features needed: SSO, SCIM, MFA.
Classification: Context (authentication is not our competitive advantage).

3-Year TCO analysis:
| Cost Factor          | Build Custom | Auth0     | Keycloak  | WorkOS    |
|----------------------|--------------|-----------|-----------|-----------|
| Initial development  | $200K        | $20K      | $80K      | $15K      |
| Annual maintenance   | $60K/yr      | $0        | $40K/yr   | $0        |
| Subscription (1K u)  | $0           | $36K/yr   | $0        | $30K/yr   |
| Infrastructure       | $12K/yr      | $0        | $24K/yr   | $0        |
| 3-Year Total         | $416K        | $128K     | $232K     | $105K     |

Strategic fit: Auth is not core. Custom build costs 4x WorkOS over 3 years.
Decision: WorkOS

Trade-offs accepted:
  Get: fastest time to market (1 month), enterprise feature coverage 98%, lowest 3-year TCO
  Lose: customization flexibility, no control over pricing changes

Exit strategy:
  1. All user data exportable via API
  2. SAML/OIDC configurations portable
  3. Backup plan: migrate to Auth0 (4-week effort)
  4. Contract includes: price cap clause, data portability clause, exit terms]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="build-evaluation">
      <p>Build evaluation checklist:</p>
      <checklist>
        <check>Capability assessment: do we have required expertise? Can we hire/develop it? What is the learning curve?</check>
        <check>Development cost: estimate realistically, include unknowns. Add 30-50% buffer for typical underestimation.</check>
        <check>Maintenance cost: typically 15-20% of development cost annually.</check>
        <check>Infrastructure cost: compute, storage, monitoring, DR.</check>
        <check>Opportunity cost: what else could the team ship in the same time?</check>
        <check>Timeline: time to MVP, time to feature parity with buy option, can we meet business deadlines?</check>
        <check>Technical risk: can we build it? Have we solved similar problems before?</check>
        <check>Schedule risk: will it take longer than estimated?</check>
        <check>Quality risk: will it work as well as a mature vendor solution?</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="buy-evaluation">
      <p>Buy evaluation checklist:</p>
      <checklist>
        <check>Vendor financial stability: publicly traded, funded, or bootstrapped with strong revenue?</check>
        <check>Market position: category leader, challenger, or niche player?</check>
        <check>Product roadmap alignment: does their roadmap match your 2-year needs?</check>
        <check>Support quality: SLA, response times, dedicated support tier?</check>
        <check>Feature fit: what percentage of requirements does this vendor meet?</check>
        <check>Gap analysis: what features are missing and what is the workaround?</check>
        <check>Customization options: can gaps be addressed via configuration, extensions, or API?</check>
        <check>Integration complexity: how difficult is integration with our current stack?</check>
        <check>3-year TCO: include license/subscription, implementation, integration, training, customization, and any per-seat scaling costs.</check>
        <check>Vendor lock-in risk: how hard is it to migrate away in 3 years?</check>
        <check>Data portability: can we export all our data in a standard format?</check>
        <check>Contract: price cap clause, data portability clause, exit/termination terms, SLA guarantees, security/compliance attestations.</check>
      </checklist>
    </section>

    <section name="hybrid-options">
      <p>Hybrid approaches to consider: buy core, build extensions; build core, integrate bought components; open source plus custom development. Evaluate integration complexity for each hybrid: does the boundary between built and bought create a maintenance burden that exceeds the benefit of buying?</p>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Choosing a hybrid approach because it feels like a safe middle ground without evaluating its integration complexity.</description>
        <reason>Hybrids often carry the operational complexity of both build and buy simultaneously. The integration seam between built and bought components is itself a maintenance surface. Quantify integration cost before choosing hybrid.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="llm-prompts">
      <prompt purpose="build vs buy initial assessment">
<![CDATA[Help me evaluate build vs buy for: [capability description]

Our context:
- Company: [size, stage, industry]
- Team: [size, expertise]
- Budget: [constraints]
- Timeline: [deadline]
- Strategic importance: [core/context/commodity]

Requirements:
- [Requirement 1]
- [Requirement 2]
- [Requirement 3]

Questions to answer:
1. Is this capability core to competitive advantage? Why/why not?
2. What is the realistic build effort (include unknowns and typical underestimation)?
3. What buy options exist? Name specific vendors/products.
4. What is the 3-year TCO comparison framework?
5. What is the key trade-off between build and buy here?

Be realistic about build complexity — include typical underestimation factors.]]>
      </prompt>

      <prompt purpose="vendor evaluation">
<![CDATA[Evaluate [Vendor A] vs [Vendor B] for [capability].

Our requirements: [list requirements with priority]

For each vendor, assess:
1. Feature fit (% of requirements met)
2. Integration complexity with [our stack]
3. Pricing model and 3-year projection
4. Vendor stability and market position
5. Lock-in risk and exit strategy
6. Hidden costs (training, customization, support)

Create a comparison table and recommendation.
Include: What questions should we ask each vendor?]]>
      </prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="key-lessons">
      <p>Key lessons from real build vs buy decisions:</p>
      <list>
        <item>Binary thinking leads to suboptimal outcomes — most examples end up choosing hybrid approaches.</item>
        <item>Ignoring exit strategy: always document how you get out before you commit to a vendor.</item>
        <item>Not considering team expertise: a technically superior solution is worthless if the team cannot operate it effectively.</item>
        <item>Underestimating operational complexity of build: a custom solution requires ongoing maintenance, security patches, and scalability work that buy options provide automatically.</item>
        <item>Treating buy as "zero maintenance": integrations, upgrades, and custom configuration still require engineering time.</item>
      </list>

      <antipattern>
        <description>Choosing to build because "we can do it better" without quantifying what better means and what it costs.</description>
        <reason>Most custom solutions reach feature parity with buy options 12-18 months after the buy option would have been deployed, while accumulating ongoing maintenance debt. Quantify the specific advantage before justifying build.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

